{"id":"2011.13794","submitter":"Luca Razzoli","authors":"Luca Razzoli, Matteo G. A. Paris, Paolo Bordone","title":"Transport efficiency of continuous-time quantum walks on graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Entropy 2021, 23(1), 85","doi":"10.3390/e23010085","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Continuous-time quantum walk describes the propagation of a quantum particle\n(or an excitation) evolving continuously in time on a graph. As such, it\nprovides a natural framework for modeling transport processes, e.g., in\nlight-harvesting systems. In particular, the transport properties strongly\ndepend on the initial state and on the specific features of the graph under\ninvestigation. In this paper, we address the role of graph topology, and\ninvestigate the transport properties of graphs with different regularity,\nsymmetry, and connectivity. We neglect disorder and decoherence, and assume a\nsingle trap vertex accountable for the loss processes. In particular, for each\ngraph, we analytically determine the subspace of states having maximum\ntransport efficiency. Our results provide a set of benchmarks for\nenvironment-assisted quantum transport, and suggest that connectivity is a poor\nindicator for transport efficiency. Indeed, we observe some specific\ncorrelations between transport efficiency and connectivity for certain graphs,\nbut in general they are uncorrelated.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Nov 2020 15:45:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 12 Jan 2021 10:45:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-02"}
